B. Modular Arithmetic
Congruence Fundamentals: 154. Definition: a ≡ b (mod n) ⟺ n|(a-b) 155. Reflexive, symmetric, transitive 156. Addition: a≡b, c≡d (mod n) ⟹ a+c≡b+d (mod n) 157. Multiplication: a≡b, c≡d (mod n) ⟹ ac≡bd (mod n) 158. Power: a≡b (mod n) ⟹ aᵏ≡bᵏ (mod n) 159. Cancellation: ac≡bc (mod n) and gcd(c,n)=1 ⟹ a≡b (mod n) 160. Division not always valid: Need multiplicative inverse

Modular Inverse: 161. Existence: a has inverse mod n ⟺ gcd(a,n)=1 162. Computation: Extended Euclidean algorithm 163. Uniqueness: Inverse unique mod n 164. Fermat's method: a^(p-1) ≡ 1 (mod p) ⟹ a^(p-2) is inverse

Major Theorems: 165. Fermat's Little Theorem: If p prime, gcd(a,p)=1, then a^(p-1) ≡ 1 (mod p) 166. Fermat's corollary: aᵖ ≡ a (mod p) for any a 167. Euler's theorem: If gcd(a,n)=1, then a^φ(n) ≡ 1 (mod n) 168. Euler's totient: φ(n) = count of k≤n with gcd(k,n)=1 169. φ(p) = p-1 for prime p 170. φ(pᵏ) = pᵏ - pᵏ⁻¹ = pᵏ⁻¹(p-1) 171. φ multiplicative: gcd(m,n)=1 ⟹ φ(mn) = φ(m)φ(n) 172. Sum of φ: Σφ(d) over d|n equals n 173. Wilson's theorem: (p-1)! ≡ -1 (mod p) for prime p 174. Chinese Remainder Theorem: System x≡aᵢ (mod nᵢ) with gcd(nᵢ,nⱼ)=1 has unique solution mod ∏nᵢ 175. CRT construction algorithm

Orders & Primitive Roots: 176. Order of a mod n: Smallest k>0 with aᵏ≡1 (mod n) 177. Order divides φ(n) 178. Primitive root: Order equals φ(n) 179. Primitive roots exist for n = 1,2,4,pᵏ,2pᵏ (p odd prime) 180. Count of primitive roots: φ(φ(n))

Quadratic Residues: 181. Definition: a is QR mod n if x²≡a (mod n) solvable 182. Legendre symbol: (a/p) = 0,1,-1 183. Euler's criterion: (a/p) ≡ a^((p-1)/2) (mod p) 184. Quadratic reciprocity: (p/q)(q/p) = (-1)^((p-1)(q-1)/4) 185. Supplement laws: (-1/p) = (-1)^((p-1)/2), (2/p) = (-1)^((p²-1)/8) 186. Jacobi symbol (generalization to composite moduli)

