Gem #91: Parabola (Standard Form) (continued)
Tier: 2
Archetype Links: #4 (Hidden Structure), #12 (Extremal)
Usage: Parabola problems, locus, reflective properties
Mastery Note: Opens rightward. Focal parameter 4a. Locus definition: point equidistant from focus and directrix. Vertical form: x²=4ay. Practice: y²=8x has a=2, focus (2,0), directrix x=-2.

Gem #92: Ellipse (Standard Form)
Statement: x²/a² + y²/b² = 1 (a>b)
Center origin, foci (±c,0) where c²=a²-b², eccentricity e=c/a
Tier: 2
Archetype Links: #2 (Symmetry), #12 (Extremal)
Usage: Ellipse problems, orbital mechanics connections
Mastery Note: a=semi-major axis, b=semi-minor axis. Sum property: PF₁+PF₂=2a for any point P on ellipse. Eccentricity 0<e<1 (circle when e=0, i.e., a=b).

Gem #93: Hyperbola (Standard Form)
Statement: x²/a² - y²/b² = 1
Center origin, foci (±c,0) where c²=a²+b², asymptotes y=±(b/a)x
Tier: 2
Archetype Links: #3 (Duality), #12 (Extremal)
Usage: Hyperbola problems, rectangular hyperbola (xy=k)
Mastery Note: Difference property: |PF₁-PF₂|=2a. Eccentricity e=c/a>1. Asymptotes approached as x→±∞. Rectangular hyperbola: xy=c² has asymptotes as coordinate axes.

DOMAIN IV: TRIGONOMETRY (17 Gems)
Section O: Basic Identities (4 Gems)
Gem #94: Pythagorean Identity
Statement: sin²θ + cos²θ = 1
Tier: 1 (Instant Recall)
Archetype Links: #1 (Invariance), #20 (Analogy to Pythagoras)
Usage: 50% of trigonometry problems, simplifying expressions
Mastery Note: Most fundamental trig identity. Derived from unit circle. Consequences: sin²θ=1-cos²θ, cos²θ=1-sin²θ. Use to convert between sin and cos.

Gem #95: Tangent Definition
Statement: tan θ = sin θ/cos θ
Tier: 1
Archetype Links: #5 (Substitution), basic
Usage: Converting between trig functions
Mastery Note: Immediate from definitions. Also: cot θ = cos θ/sin θ = 1/tan θ.

Gem #96: Pythagorean Identity (Tangent)
Statement: 1 + tan²θ = sec²θ
Tier: 1
Archetype Links: #1 (Invariance), derivative of tan
Usage: Simplifying tangent/secant expressions, calculus
Mastery Note: Derived from Gem #94 by dividing by cos²θ. Also: 1 + cot²θ = csc²θ (divide by sin²θ).

Gem #97: Cotangent Identity
Statement: 1 + cot²θ = csc²θ
Tier: 2
Archetype Links: #1 (Invariance)
Usage: Less common than Gem #96, but symmetric
Mastery Note: Parallel to Gem #96. From Gem #94, divide by sin²θ.

Section P: Angle Sum & Multiple Angle (6 Gems)
Gem #98: Sine Addition
Statement: sin(A ± B) = sin A cos B ± cos A sin B
Tier: 1 (Instant Recall)
Archetype Links: #5 (Substitution), #6 (Linearization)
Usage: 30% of trig problems, expanding compound angles
Mastery Note: Critical for angle manipulation. Plus for addition, minus for subtraction. Practice: sin 75° = sin(45°+30°) = (√6+√2)/4.

Gem #99: Cosine Addition
Statement: cos(A ± B) = cos A cos B ∓ sin A sin B
Tier: 1 (Instant Recall)
Archetype Links: #5 (Substitution), #6 (Linearization)
Usage: 30% of trig problems, Law of Cosines derivation
Mastery Note: Note sign reversal: minus for addition, plus for subtraction (opposite of sine). Practice: cos 15° = cos(45°-30°) = (√6+√2)/4.

Gem #100: Tangent Addition
Statement: tan(A ± B) = (tan A ± tan B)/(1 ∓ tan A tan B)
Tier: 2
Archetype Links: #5 (Substitution)
Usage: Tangent problems, angle conversions
Mastery Note: Derived from Gems #98, #99 by dividing. Plus in numerator, minus in denominator for addition (reverse for subtraction).

Gem #101: Double Angle (Sine)
Statement: sin 2θ = 2 sin θ cos θ
Tier: 1
Archetype Links: #5 (Substitution), #6 (Linearization)
Usage: Simplifying products, half-angle problems
Mastery Note: Special case of Gem #98 with A=B=θ. Bidirectional: 2sin θ cos θ = sin 2θ (useful for simplification).

Gem #102: Double Angle (Cosine)
Statement: cos 2θ = cos²θ - sin²θ = 2cos²θ - 1 = 1 - 2sin²θ
Tier: 1
Archetype Links: #5 (Substitution), #6 (Linearization)
Usage: Multiple forms useful for different contexts
Mastery Note: Three equivalent forms. From Gem #99 with A=B=θ, then use Gem #94 for other two. Choose form based on problem: need cos²? Use 2cos²θ-1. Need sin²? Use 1-2sin²θ.

Gem #103: Double Angle (Tangent)
Statement: tan 2θ = 2tan θ/(1 - tan²θ)
Tier: 2
Archetype Links: #5 (Substitution)
Usage: Tangent doubling
Mastery Note: From Gem #100 with A=B=θ. Less common than sine/cosine double angles.

Section Q: Product-to-Sum & Sum-to-Product (7 Gems)
Gem #104: Product-to-Sum (sin sin)
Statement: sin A sin B = ½[cos(A-B) - cos(A+B)]
Tier: 2
Archetype Links: #6 (Linearization), #5 (Substitution)
Usage: Simplifying products, integration
Mastery Note: Derived from Gems #98, #99 by adding/subtracting. Pattern: sin·sin gives cos (with minus). Useful for turning products into sums.

Gem #105: Product-to-Sum (cos cos)
Statement: cos A cos B = ½[cos(A-B) + cos(A+B)]
Tier: 2
Archetype Links: #6 (Linearization), #5 (Substitution)
Usage: Simplifying products, integrals
Mastery Note: Pattern: cos·cos gives cos (with plus). Symmetric with Gem #104.

Gem #106: Product-to-Sum (sin cos)
Statement: sin A cos B = ½[sin(A+B) + sin(A-B)]
Tier: 2
Archetype Links: #6 (Linearization), #5 (Substitution)
Usage: Mixed products
Mastery Note: Pattern: sin·cos gives sin (both sum and difference). Order matters: cos A sin B = ½[sin(A+B) - sin(A-B)] (different signs).

Gem #107: Sum-to-Product (sin + sin)
Statement: sin A + sin B = 2sin[(A+B)/2]cos[(A-B)/2]
Tier: 2
Archetype Links: #6 (Linearization), #19 (Factoring)
Usage: Simplifying sums, proving identities
Mastery Note: Inverse of product-to-sum. Use substitutions: let (A+B)/2=x, (A-B)/2=y, then A=x+y, B=x-y. Pattern: sin+sin → 2·sin·cos.

Gem #108: Sum-to-Product (sin - sin)
Statement: sin A - sin B = 2cos[(A+B)/2]sin[(A-B)/2]
Tier: 2
Archetype Links: #6 (Linearization), #19 (Factoring)
Usage: Simplifying differences
Mastery Note: Pattern: sin-sin → 2·cos·sin. Note order: cos comes first (opposite of addition).

Gem #109: Sum-to-Product (cos + cos)
Statement: cos A + cos B = 2cos[(A+B)/2]cos[(A-B)/2]
Tier: 2
Archetype Links: #6 (Linearization), #19 (Factoring)
Usage: Simplifying sums
Mastery Note: Pattern: cos+cos → 2·cos·cos. Both factors are cosine.

Gem #110: Sum-to-Product (cos - cos)
Statement: cos A - cos B = -2sin[(A+B)/2]sin[(A-B)/2]
Tier: 2
Archetype Links: #6 (Linearization), #19 (Factoring)
Usage: Simplifying differences
Mastery Note: Note negative sign. Pattern: cos-cos → -2·sin·sin. Only one with minus.

DOMAIN V: COMBINATORICS (24 Gems)
Section R: Basic Counting (8 Gems)
Gem #111: Permutations
Statement: P(n,r) = n!/(n-r)! = number of ways to arrange r objects from n
Tier: 1 (Instant Recall)
Archetype Links: #13 (Combinatorics), #17 (Degrees of Freedom)
Usage: 40% of counting problems, ordered arrangements
Mastery Note: Order matters. Special case: P(n,n) = n!. Practice: P(5,3) = 5·4·3 = 60.

Gem #112: Combinations
Statement: C(n,r) = n!/[r!(n-r)!] = number of ways to choose r objects from n
Tier: 1 (Instant Recall)
Archetype Links: #13 (Combinatorics), #17 (Degrees of Freedom)
Usage: 50% of counting problems, unordered selections
Mastery Note: Order doesn't matter. Relation to permutations: C(n,r) = P(n,r)/r!. Practice: C(5,3) = 10.

Gem #113: Permutations with Repetition
Statement: n!/(n₁!n₂!...nₖ!) where nᵢ are counts of identical objects
Tier: 2
Archetype Links: #13 (Combinatorics), #7 (Normalization)
Usage: Arrangements with identical objects, anagrams
Mastery Note: Divide by factorials of repetitions to avoid overcounting. Practice: arrangements of MISSISSIPPI = 11!/(4!·4!·2!) since I appears 4 times, S appears 4 times, P appears 2 times.

Gem #114: Circular Permutations
Statement: (n-1)! ways to arrange n objects in a circle
Tier: 2
Archetype Links: #13 (Combinatorics), #2 (Symmetry)
Usage: Circular arrangement problems, necklace problems
Mastery Note: Fix one object to break rotational symmetry, arrange remaining (n-1) objects. If reflections identical (like a necklace), divide by 2: (n-1)!/2.

Gem #115: Symmetry Property of Combinations
Statement: C(n,r) = C(n,n-r)
Tier: 1
Archetype Links: #2 (Symmetry), #15 (Bijection)
Usage: Simplifying binomial coefficients, bijection proofs
Mastery Note: Choosing r objects = leaving out n-r objects. Bijection between selections. Use to simplify: C(100,98) = C(100,2) = 4950.

Gem #116: Pascal's Identity
Statement: C(n,r) = C(n-1,r-1) + C(n-1,r)
Tier: 2
Archetype Links: #18 (Recursion), #13 (Combinatorics)
Usage: Pascal's triangle, induction, combinatorial proofs
Mastery Note: Recursive structure of binomial coefficients. Either include or exclude a particular object. Basis of Pascal's triangle construction.

Gem #117: Binomial Row Sum
Statement: Σ C(n,r) from r=0 to n = 2ⁿ
Tier: 2
Archetype Links: #15 (Bijection), #13 (Combinatorics)
Usage: Counting subsets, power set
Mastery Note: Proof: set a=b=1 in Gem #12 (binomial theorem). Interpretation: total number of subsets of n-element set = 2ⁿ (each element either in or out).

Gem #118: Alternating Binomial Sum
Statement: Σ(-1)ʳC(n,r) from r=0 to n = 0
Tier: 2
Archetype Links: #15 (Bijection), #13 (Combinatorics)
Usage: Inclusion-exclusion, bijection proofs
Mastery Note: Proof: set a=1, b=-1 in Gem #12. Interpretation: even-sized subsets = odd-sized subsets (for n≥1).

Section S: Stars and Bars & Inclusion-Exclusion (6 Gems)
Gem #119: Stars and Bars (Non-negative)
Statement: Number of non-negative integer solutions to x₁+...+xₖ=n is C(n+k-1, k-1)
Tier: 2
Archetype Links: #13 (Combinatorics), #15 (Bijection)
Usage: Distribution problems, weak compositions
Mastery Note: Bijection with arrangements of n stars and k-1 bars. Practice: x+y+z=5 → C(5+3-1,3-1) = C(7,2) = 21 solutions.

Gem #120: Stars and Bars (Positive)
Statement: Number of positive integer solutions to x₁+...+xₖ=n is C(n-1, k-1)
Tier: 2
Archetype Links: #13 (Combinatorics), #5 (Substitution)
Usage: Distribution with minimum requirements
Mastery Note: Transform via yᵢ=xᵢ-1≥0, then y₁+...+yₖ=n-k, apply Gem #119. Practice: x+y+z=5 (positive) → C(5-1,3-1) = C(4,2) = 6 solutions.

Gem #121: Inclusion-Exclusion (2 sets)
Statement: |A∪B| = |A| + |B| - |A∩B|
Tier: 1
Archetype Links: #13 (Combinatorics), #19 (Pivoting - adding then subtracting)
Usage: Counting unions, probability
Mastery Note: Subtract intersection to avoid double-counting. Foundation for general principle.

Gem #122: Inclusion-Exclusion (3 sets)
Statement: |A∪B∪C| = |A|+|B|+|C| - |A∩B| - |B∩C| - |C∩A| + |A∩B∩C|
Tier: 1
Archetype Links: #13 (Combinatorics), #19 (Pivoting)
Usage: Three-set counting problems
Mastery Note: Alternating signs: add singles, subtract pairs, add triple. Pattern continues for n sets.

Gem #123: Derangements
Statement: !n = n!(1 - 1/1! + 1/2! - 1/3! + ... + (-1)ⁿ/n!)
Number of permutations with no fixed points
Tier: 2
Archetype Links: #13 (Combinatorics), inclusion-exclusion
Usage: "No one gets their own hat" problems, olympiad counting
Mastery Note: Derived via inclusion-exclusion. Approximation: !n ≈ n!/e. Values: !2=1, !3=2, !4=9, !5=44.

Gem #124: Counting Surjections
Statement: Number of onto functions from n-set to k-set (n≥k) via inclusion-exclusion:
Σ(-1)ʲC(k,j)(k-j)ⁿ for j=0 to k
Tier: 2
Archetype Links: #13 (Combinatorics), #16 (Reverse Engineering)
Usage: Advanced counting, olympiad
Mastery Note: Total functions kⁿ, subtract those missing at least one element. Complex but powerful for onto-counting.

Section T: Pigeonhole Principle (3 Gems)
Gem #125: Pigeonhole Principle (Basic)
Statement: If n+1 objects placed in n boxes, some box contains ≥2 objects
Tier: 1 (Instant Recall)
Archetype Links: #11 (Existence), #12 (Extremal)
Usage: 20% of olympiad problems, existence proofs
Mastery Note: Simple but powerful. Existence proof technique: show something must exist without constructing it. Practice: 13 people → two share birth month (12 boxes).

Gem #126: Generalized Pigeonhole
Statement: If kn+1 objects in n boxes, some box has ≥k+1 objects
Tier: 1
Archetype Links: #11 (Existence), #12 (Extremal)
Usage: Stronger bounds, advanced olympiad
Mastery Note: Generalization of Gem #125 (k=1 case). Proof by contradiction: if all boxes have ≤k, total ≤kn < kn+1.

Gem #127: Average Pigeonhole
Statement: If average value is μ, then max ≥ μ and min ≤ μ
Tier: 2
Archetype Links: #12 (Extremal), #10 (Inequality)
Usage: Average arguments, existence of extremes
Mastery Note: Continuous version. If all values were < μ, average < μ (contradiction). Practice: average score 75 → someone scored ≥75.

Section U: Graph Theory Basics (4 Gems)
Gem #128: Handshaking Lemma
Statement: In any graph: Σ deg(v) = 2|E|
(Sum of degrees = twice number of edges)
Tier: 1
Archetype Links: #1 (Invariance), #13 (Combinatorics - double counting)
Usage: Graph theory problems, parity arguments
Mastery Note: Each edge contributes 2 to degree sum (one at each endpoint). Corollary: number of odd-degree vertices is even.

Gem #129: Tree Edge Count
Statement: Tree with n vertices has exactly n-1 edges
Tier: 1
Archetype Links: #1 (Invariance), #17 (Degrees of Freedom)
Usage: Tree problems, connectivity
Mastery Note: Characterization: connected + acyclic ⟺ n vertices, n-1 edges. Adding one edge creates exactly one cycle; removing one edge disconnects.

Gem #130: Euler Circuit Condition
Statement: Connected graph has Euler circuit ⟺ all vertices have even degree
Tier: 2
Archetype Links: #11 (Existence), #14 (Parity)
Usage: Path problems, "draw without lifting pen"
Mastery Note: Euler circuit visits every edge exactly once, returns to start. Euler path (not circuit) exists ⟺ exactly 0 or 2 odd-degree vertices.

Gem #131: Euler Path Condition
Statement: Connected graph has Euler path ⟺ exactly 0 or 2 vertices have odd degree
Tier: 2
Archetype Links: #11 (Existence), #14 (Parity)
Usage: Path existence problems
Mastery Note: 0 odd-degree → Euler circuit (special case of path). 2 odd-degree → path exists, starts at one odd vertex, ends at other.

Section V: Additional Counting (3 Gems - Specialized)
Gem #132: Catalan Numbers
Statement: Cₙ = C(2n,n)/(n+1) = number of balanced parentheses, binary trees, paths not crossing diagonal
Tier: 2
Archetype Links: #18 (Recursion), #13 (Combinatorics)
Usage: Advanced olympiad counting, structural problems
Mastery Note: Recurrence: C₀=1, Cₙ=ΣCᵢCₙ₋₁₋ᵢ. Values: C₀=1, C₁=1, C₂=2, C₃=5, C₄=14, C₅=42. Recognition-level; know it exists for specialized counting.

Gem #133: Stirling Numbers (Second Kind)
Statement: S(n,k) = number of ways to partition n objects into k non-empty subsets
Recurrence: S(n,k) = kS(n-1,k) + S(n-1,k-1)
Tier: 2
Archetype Links: #18 (Recursion), #13 (Combinatorics)
Usage: Set partition problems, advanced counting
Mastery Note: Recognition-level. Bell numbers Bₙ = ΣS(n,k) (total partitions). Example: S(3,2)=3 (ways to partition {1,2,3} into 2 subsets: {{1},{2,3}}, {{2},{1,3}}, {{3},{1,2}}).

Gem #134: Vandermonde's Identity
Statement: C(m+n,r) = Σ C(m,k)C(n,r-k) for k=0 to r
Tier: 2
Archetype Links: #15 (Bijection), #13 (Combinatorics)
Usage: Binomial coefficient identities, combinatorial proofs
Mastery Note: Bijection proof: choose r from m+n = choose k from first m, r-k from remaining n. Special case m=n=r: C(2n,n) = Σ[C(n,k)]².

DOMAIN VI: SEQUENCES & SERIES (9 Gems)
Section W: Arithmetic & Geometric Progressions (6 Gems)
Gem #135: Arithmetic Progression (General Term)
Statement: aₙ = a₁ + (n-1)d
Tier: 1 (Instant Recall)
Archetype Links: #6 (Linearization), #18 (Recursion)
Usage: AP problems, finding nth term
Mastery Note: Common difference d. Linear growth. Practice: 2,5,8,11,... → a₁=2, d=3, a₁₀=2+9·3=29.

Gem #136: Arithmetic Series Sum
Statement: Sₙ = n(2a₁+(n-1)d)/2 = n(a₁+aₙ)/2
Tier: 1
Archetype Links: #19 (Pivoting - pair terms), #6 (Linearization)
Usage: Sum of AP, average value
Mastery Note: Two forms: terms of d, or first/last term. Proof: reverse series, add pairwise. Practice: 1+2+...+100 = 100·101/2 = 5050.

Gem #137: Sum of First n Integers
Statement: 1+2+...+n = n(n+1)/2
Tier: 1
Archetype Links: Special case of Gem #136
Usage: Most common sum, appears everywhere
Mastery Note: Gauss's childhood trick. Memorize values: Σ10=55, Σ20=210, Σ100=5050.

Gem #138: Geometric Progression (General Term)
Statement: aₙ = a₁rⁿ⁻¹
Tier: 1
Archetype Links: #5 (Substitution), #18 (Recursion)
Usage: GP problems, exponential growth
Mastery Note: Common ratio r. Exponential growth (r>1) or decay (0<r<1). Practice: 3,6,12,24,... → a₁=3, r=2, a₈=3·2⁷=384.

Gem #139: Geometric Series Sum (Finite)
Statement: Sₙ = a₁(1-rⁿ)/(1-r) = a₁(rⁿ-1)/(r-1) for r≠1
Tier: 1
Archetype Links: #19 (Telescoping), #5 (Substitution)
Usage: GP sums, compound interest
Mastery Note: Two forms (choose to avoid negative denominator). If r=1, Sₙ=na₁. Practice: 1+2+4+8+...+512 = 1·(2⁹-1)/(2-1) = 511.

Gem #140: Geometric Series Sum (Infinite)
Statement: S = a₁/(1-r) for |r|<1
Tier: 1
Archetype Links: #6 (Linearization), convergence
Usage: Infinite series, calculus
Mastery Note: Converges only when |r|<1. As n→∞, rⁿ→0. Practice: 1+½+¼+⅛+... = 1/(1-½) = 2.

Section X: Special Sums (3 Gems)
Gem #141: Sum of Squares
Statement: 1²+2²+...+n² = n(n+1)(2n+1)/6
Tier: 2
Archetype Links: #4 (Hidden Structure), #18 (Induction)
Usage: Squared sums, induction problems
Mastery Note: Proof by induction or telescoping (k³-(k-1)³). Practice: 1²+2²+...+10² = 10·11·21/6 = 385.

Gem #142: Sum of Cubes
Statement: 1³+2³+...+n³ = [n(n+1)/2]² = (Σk)²
Tier: 2
Archetype Links: #20 (Analogy - square of triangular number), #4 (Hidden Structure)
Usage: Cubed sums, beautiful identity
Mastery Note: Remarkably, equals square of Gem #137. Practice: 1³+2³+3³+4³ = (1+2+3+4)² = 10² = 100.

Gem #143: Telescoping Series
Statement: Σ(aₙ - aₙ₊₁) from n=1 to N = a₁ - aₙ₊₁
Tier: 1
Archetype Links: #19 (Pivoting/Cancellation), #4 (Hidden Structure)
Usage: Collapsing sums, partial fractions
Mastery Note: Middle terms cancel. Practice: Σ1/(k(k+1)) = Σ(1/k - 1/(k+1)) = 1 - 1/(N+1) → 1 as N→∞.

DOMAIN VII: CALCULUS (13 Gems - for JEE)
Section Y: Differentiation (8 Gems)
Gem #144: Power Rule
Statement: d/dx(xⁿ) = nxⁿ⁻¹
Tier: 1 (Instant Recall)
Archetype Links: #5 (Substitution), basic
Usage: 80% of differentiation
Mastery Note: Most fundamental derivative. Works for any real n (including negative, fractional). Practice: d/dx(x³)=3x², d/dx(1/x)=d/dx(x⁻¹)=-x⁻²=-1/x².

Gem #145: Product Rule
Statement: d/dx(fg) = f'g + fg'
Tier: 1
Archetype Links: #6 (Linearization), composition
Usage: Differentiating products
Mastery Note: Don't forget both terms. Practice: d/dx(x²sin x) = 2x sin x + x²cos x.

Gem #146: Quotient Rule
Statement: d/dx(f/g) = (f'g - fg')/g²
Tier: 1
Archetype Links: #19 (Pivoting), composition
Usage: Differentiating fractions
Mastery Note: "Low d-high minus high d-low, over low squared." Practice: d/dx(sin x/x) = (x cos x - sin x)/x².

Gem #147: Chain Rule
Statement: d/dx[f(g(x))] = f'(g(x))·g'

Continue

Jan 1
Gem #147: Chain Rule (continued)
Statement: d/dx[f(g(x))] = f'(g(x))·g'(x)
Tier: 1 (Instant Recall)
Archetype Links: #5 (Substitution), composition
Usage: Composite functions, 60% of calculus problems
Mastery Note: "Derivative of outside times derivative of inside." Practice: d/dx(sin(x²)) = cos(x²)·2x. Most important derivative rule after power rule.

Gem #148: Derivative of sin x
Statement: d/dx(sin x) = cos x
Tier: 1
Archetype Links: Basic, trigonometry
Usage: Trig derivatives, oscillation problems
Mastery Note: Memorize the cycle: sin→cos→-sin→-cos→sin. Practice with chain rule: d/dx(sin 3x) = 3cos 3x.

Gem #149: Derivative of cos x
Statement: d/dx(cos x) = -sin x
Tier: 1
Archetype Links: Basic, trigonometry
Usage: Trig derivatives
Mastery Note: Note the negative sign. Pair with Gem #148 for trig calculus.

Gem #150: Derivative of tan x
Statement: d/dx(tan x) = sec²x
Tier: 2
Archetype Links: #5 (Substitution), follows from Gems #148-149
Usage: Tangent derivatives
Mastery Note: Derived from d/dx(sin x/cos x) using quotient rule. Also: d/dx(cot x) = -csc²x.

Gem #151: Derivative of eˣ
Statement: d/dx(eˣ) = eˣ
Tier: 1
Archetype Links: #1 (Invariance), special property
Usage: Exponential growth, differential equations
Mastery Note: Unique property: function equals its derivative. Foundation of exponential modeling. Practice: d/dx(e^(2x)) = 2e^(2x).

Gem #152: Derivative of ln x
Statement: d/dx(ln x) = 1/x
Tier: 1
Archetype Links: #5 (Substitution), inverse of exponential
Usage: Logarithmic differentiation, integration
Mastery Note: Only defined for x>0. Integral form: ∫(1/x)dx = ln|x| + C. Practice: d/dx(ln(x²)) = 2/x.

Section Z: Integration (5 Gems)
Gem #153: Power Rule (Integration)
Statement: ∫xⁿ dx = xⁿ⁺¹/(n+1) + C for n≠-1
Tier: 1 (Instant Recall)
Archetype Links: #5 (Substitution), reverse of Gem #144
Usage: 70% of integration
Mastery Note: Reverse power rule. Increase exponent by 1, divide by new exponent. Practice: ∫x³dx = x⁴/4 + C. Exception: n=-1 gives ln (Gem #154).

Gem #154: Integral of 1/x
Statement: ∫(1/x)dx = ln|x| + C
Tier: 1
Archetype Links: #5 (Substitution), special case
Usage: Logarithmic integration
Mastery Note: Exception to Gem #153. Absolute value for negative x. Practice: ∫(2/x)dx = 2ln|x| + C.

Gem #155: Integral of eˣ
Statement: ∫eˣ dx = eˣ + C
Tier: 1
Archetype Links: #1 (Invariance), reverse of Gem #151
Usage: Exponential integrals
Mastery Note: Simplest integral. ∫e^(ax)dx = (1/a)e^(ax) + C. Practice: ∫e^(3x)dx = (1/3)e^(3x) + C.

Gem #156: Integral of sin x
Statement: ∫sin x dx = -cos x + C
Tier: 1
Archetype Links: Reverse of Gem #149
Usage: Trig integration
Mastery Note: Note negative sign (from derivative of cos). Practice: ∫sin 2x dx = -½cos 2x + C.

Gem #157: Integral of cos x
Statement: ∫cos x dx = sin x + C
Tier: 1
Archetype Links: Reverse of Gem #148
Usage: Trig integration
Mastery Note: Positive sign. Pair with Gem #156.

Gem #158: Integration by Parts
Statement: ∫u dv = uv - ∫v du
Tier: 2
Archetype Links: #19 (Pivoting), reverse of product rule
Usage: Product integrals, reduction formulas
Mastery Note: Choose u via LIATE rule (Logarithmic, Inverse trig, Algebraic, Trig, Exponential). Practice: ∫x·eˣdx → u=x, dv=eˣdx → x·eˣ - ∫eˣdx = xeˣ - eˣ + C.

Gem #159: Fundamental Theorem of Calculus
Statement: ∫ₐᵇ f(x)dx = F(b) - F(a) where F'(x) = f(x)
Tier: 1
Archetype Links: #1 (Invariance), connects derivative/integral
Usage: Evaluating definite integrals
Mastery Note: Most important theorem in calculus. Links differentiation and integration. Practice: ∫₁³ x²dx = [x³/3]₁³ = 27/3 - 1/3 = 26/3.

Gem #160: Standard Limits
Statement:

lim(x→0) (sin x)/x = 1
lim(x→0) (eˣ-1)/x = 1
lim(x→∞) (1+1/x)ˣ = e
Tier: 2
Archetype Links: #6 (Linearization), fundamental limits
Usage: Limit evaluation, L'Hôpital setup
